Alt_Area: and set off on the 90 minute journey just as

Hillnumber: broken high-level cloud with much sunshine. Stopped the car to take the
classic wasdale photo and arrived at overbeck bridge CP
in the car park.Yewbarrow looked great in the morning sunshine. I took
my time going up and began to talk to God.Felt the Lord reminded me about
the qualities of a knight that He is wanting to work into my life at the
moment. These are qualities which are not primarily about skill with weapons
but more about having a disciplined and prudent life
and alert. A lifestyle which has no dichotomy of 'on the field prowess'
and 'off-the-field laziness'.
The Lord then brought my attention to the parable of the workers of the
vineyard- how carefully guarded the vineyard was. The vineyard represents
my prescious relationship with God. I guess the Lord began speaking to
me about this in Lanzarote with the story of samson catching the 300 foxes.
Here the vineyard had a wall round it and a watchtower was build. This
signifies a constant watchfulness against enemies who would come to 'kill
steal and destoy' within. As my relationship with God is centred on my
heart
Arearef: the heart is also like the vineyard
Alt_Area: and here again I was reminded

Hillnumber: of the pleading of the Holy Spirit with me to 'above all else
heart for it is the wellspring of life'.
So the Lord is wanting me to develop this watchfulness
guarding of my heart and of my relationship with him. To ensure that at
all times the watchtower is manned properly. If it is not
open invitation for the enemy to attack.
Then the Lord began to speak to me about diligence
that He has provided for me. I remembered the scripture "Awake o
Zion
Arearef: ...shake off your dust.. free yourself from the chains on your neck".

Hillnumber: He has won the victory and now He says to me "Free yourself!"
He showed me that He has prepared a table before me in the presence of
my enemies. Yet it is the dilligent who enter in to the abundance of the
inheritence. Shockingly the Holy Spirit then spoke to me a scripture from
proverbs which I looked up later: "The sluggard buries his hand in
the dish
Arearef: he is too lazy to bring it back to his mouth". Yet I can

Hillnumber: see that it is our responsibility to bring to food to our mouths. He will
not feed us! He has provided a glorious inheritance
before us and invited us to sit down and eat. Diligence enables our souls
'to be satisfied with the richest of fare'. For me over the past few years
God has opened up the glorious riches of my inheritance in the saints.
It is now for me to take hold of it. "We do not want to become lazy
but to imitate those who through faith and patience inherit the promises."
Up the top of the southern face gully near bell rib I nearly took wrong
turn
Arearef: keeping too far to the right I found myself facing a rock passage

Hillnumber: maybe 10 inches wide and 6 feet high leading up. I though better of it
skirted to the left
Arearef: found that I was at the 'great door'. The little passage

Hillnumber: ended abruptly in a large drop! Moseyed up to the top by 11:30 and had
a coffee and some whisky from the hip flask! Marker.
This is where 1 hour 45 minutes of frenzied activity began as I realised
that time was now very short for me to get to Steeple. In one hour I descended
off Yewbarrow via Stirrup Crag and reached the summit of Red Pike. Marker
(s). Other dram of whisky and I set off
Arearef: eating my sandwiches out of my

Hillnumber: fleece pocket
Arearef: the next objective being Scoat Fell by 1pm to give me a

Hillnumber: chance of getting to Steeple. Not quite! I got to Scoat fell by 1:15 and
decided it was time to take it easy again and pray. Marker. Every man
and his dog (literally) was crowding onto the summit of Steeple so I decided
to head off into the tranquility of the descent towards the head of Nether
Beck. This was lovely. So tranquil and as I enjoyed the solitude Gods
presence was heavy on me. This is why I come up here. In many ways I'm
searching for this tranquility and the summits themselves become almost
meaningless when I find God like this.
So I took valley of Nether Beck to amble back. After a while I became
increasingly drawn to the mass of Middle Fell before me. I began to think
about taking a little detour. Did I have time? Yes if I bombed it! Perhaps
I should have just ambled back enjoying Gods presence? Anyway it was fun.
I decided on a route to tackle Middle fell
Arearef: and set time targets for the

Hillnumber: start of the ascent
Arearef: reaching the initial ridge between Seatallan and

Hillnumber: Middle Fell and reaching the summit. The tough bit was striking straight
up to the ridge next to the first of two streams flowing NE towards Nether
Beck. I made time on each of the targets but by the time I got the the
final ascent my legs were telling me that this was a little too much!
On top at 3:10 for the sunset over the Irish Sea. Marker.
I had a long way to travel yet as the path down took me away from the
car into the next valley
Arearef: Greendale with a three-mile walk to finish off

Hillnumber: along the road. It could just see my way to the car.

Crag about language learning - always remember that language is only

Hillnumber: park. We were legally allowed to do so

a telling off. I was chuffed to see how my -gentle answer turned
away wrath- with the local gent who wished us a good day on the fells
as we left.
When I'm walking with Ross there is no need to pay any attention to the
map. He is equipped with sufficient gear to survive the worst weather
imaginable. A top-of-the-range GPS makes navigation childs-play. There
was a little mist shrouding the top of Ingleborough though by the time
we got to the top this had cleared somewhat. Cloud cover kept breaking
to reveal surprise views.
We took shelter just off top and had the luxury of a newly brewed hot

of roughing it in this country are very much tainted by the all consuming
effect eczema had on those experiences. I just wanted to go home.

Start of walk was a bit bizarre This Guy-like effigy on top of a 30' high totem poll made of
rusty old barrels greeted us as we entered Kettlewell. There was some kind of urban scarecrow
building contest going on. Or was it to scare outlanders away. The welcome was warmer than
in Horton-in-Ribblesdale. There was no chance this time of starting the Kettlewell riots.
A beautiful clear day with great visability a little wind awaited us. We climbed out of kellewell
on our way towards Hag Dike. Ross's map route choice came slightly into question as he
crossed the stream precariously. I decided to assert my independence and backtracked to
the safety of the path.
Next bit of excitement was the finding of my first geocache. Ross trusted me with his
GPS which I misread and had us wandering about in the wrong direction. I finally found it
at N 54Degrees 09.366 W 002Degrees 00.975
Arearef: called "Which? ditch". It had a scouting theme

Hillnumber: in full view of the Ben Rhydding Scouting centre (empty that day). Could have taken a
woggle or a lump of blue john.
Just as we got to the summit of Great Whernside things turned for the worse as a) we
met the first fellow walkers of the day and b)the cloud rolled in from the nidderdale side.
Ross rushed off to get a glimpse of nidderdale before all disappeared. Actually
weather did improve after this
Arearef: though the clear skies had gone.

Hillnumber: Now for a bit of luxury as Madame Chaule gets out her methane stove
sundry accoutrements. Soon were supping hot chocolate ( and claymore whisky in my
case. I  declined not to offer Ross any whisky after his comments earlier about its
dehydrating effects!). There was one minor hitch in the process when the methane
stove exploded. Ross put out the conflagration and congratulated himself that he
had followed best advice in planting the bomb a few feet away from us.
We walked along the ridge towards little whernside
a nicer shaped mountain than its big brother. Great views of upper nidderdale from
the location of the Nidd Head Spring. We didnt spend much time at the location of the
spring so I can only say that we were in roughly the right place. We then followed the
ridge NE until we picked up the footpath going roughtly SE towards Tor Dike. This
was a traditional dales boggy trudge. At Cam Head we took the track S through
Cam pasture
Its great to walk with friends. I suppose I feel slightly that walking to me is time when
I can catch up with my best friend and have prescious time with Him - so feel a little
frustrated that there was no chance of this in all the hours away which I had today.

MVBC mens weekend away at Low Mill Outdoor Centre at Askrigg in Wensleydale.

Hillnumber: Yesterday was an all-action event with high ropes
Arearef: gorge walking and night walk down the roman road from the end of this walk to the pub in Askrigg. The only options today were Hell's Gill gorgewalk involving no-opt out dive into deep plunge-poll and swim. Or canoeing. I.e.  both options not so comfortable for someone who can swim about 10ft across a swimming pool after a but of practice.

Hillnumber: Ross and Dave Newall also opted for this option. But the party of 3 split into an A party (myself) who unanimously wanted to climb up to Drumaldrace from Gayle and a B party who were content to repeat much of the same ground of yesterdays night walk. So we set a rendez-vous point ( about SD 882 874 ) to meet for the traditional Ross Rapid-boil hot chocolate. Ross handed me the only map which we had. Both of us had GPS. Ross prefers not to use his deluxe GPS but rely on ML (Mountain Leadship) skills  and there is certain difference of emphasis
Alt_Area: in our reliance on GPS. Suffice to say that once the car was out of sight
AreaLinkID: the map was briefly used but chiefly to plot the rendez-vous point into the GPS! This I later confessed to Ross who's school-masterly look of dissappointment I took secret delight in!

Hillnumber: Headed straight for the rendez-vous across fields. My path came across an elderly farmer
with about 3.5 teeth in an age-old wool jumper. Like a lost sheep I said "Am I in the right place?". He was accomodating and pointed  the way for me to continue trespassing.

I was determined to beat the two lads to the RV so yomped from here on in. It was about 3 clicks and quite an ascent.  Only my lack of trust in the GPS cost me time in the end! I arrived at the RV 5 mins after the lads to find the water no even on the boil.
The reward for my solo A party was that I was treated to a visit to the summit alone
Arearef: and had time to pray a little and leave a marker. The weekends highlight for me though was Saturday mornings quite time when God spoke to me that I am not defined any longer as someone who has a "love deficit" but by 1 Tim 1:14 "The grace of our Lord Jesus  was poured out on me abundantly along with the faith and love that are in Christ Jesus". This was my experience  this weekend in this high intensity extrovert environment -I was filled with resources for all and evething that  came my way.

Hillnumber: this was the obvious one with the extra interest of visiting
Burton Leonard. Did a bit of research on Burton Leonard Cricket
Club and found their website. A section on club history included
a photo of the 1950 team with Dad in the front row!
Stepped off at wormald green and had a look at the first
historical marker - the George Inn pub where the Diggles had their
golden? wedding. It is now up for sale at auction in June.
First part of the walk followed a footpath over fields and
arriving at the perfect place to spy out old ground - the
score board of the cricket club near Peter Lane.
The "Monkton Mains" farm had redirected the footpath
without any indication away from the farm. So I had decided
to get out of view of the farm buildings (had already met
the farmer) and "off road" back onto the footpath position
using the GPS. It turned out that the re-routed footpath
followed the exact position I was going to take! Sat
down for a coffee and listened to the peace of the
countryside. How I need this space. I have been unable to
get any time to unwind since christmas with Linda not
being well
I was going to use the time to re-think what I am
currently doing because it has become clear to me that its
too much at the moment to carry. Talking to Pete during the
week was great as it became clear to both of us that
I obviously need to cut stuff out or I will go under. The
list of church responsibilities at present - elder
worship once a month
housegroup. Add to this the stress of Linda not being in
a good place with the operation and the stress of all
the issues around adoption. I could do all the church if
things were good at home- but they-re not.
Most of the day I just walked slowly
surroundings. I was walking in a gently rolling
landscape of fields descending to the Vale of York around
the middle of the day
More and more I can appreciate walks such as this without
the grandeur of mountain scenery. I took the book on wild
flowers I bought in February at York with the aim of
identifying my first wild flower.
Excitiment mounted as I approached the outskirts of Burton
Leonard. I suddenly came upon the score-board building of
BLCC. Taking a leak round the back I wondered if my Dad
had ever peed in the same spot?!
My next task was to spy out the Wrays house on Peter Lane
take some photos and move on un-noticed. The old scrap
yard at the edge of their house has been sold and three
houses have been built on the site
been built right up against the boundary. I walked
out into the central green space of the village. The
next ritual was to buy something at the village store
and sit in the shelter opposite with a coffee and watch
the village go by.
Next stop was the church opposite where Ladbroke House used
to be. Lost of old trees including a baby yew taken
cutting from the 2000 year old Buxted yew. It is one of 7000 yews
distributed in Autumn 1999 from cuttings of
ancient yews to mark the millenium.
I actually recognised two mature Scots Pines nearest
to Ladbroke House and remembered looking out of the sitting room
window at their straight trunks.
Last mandatory stop on memory lane was to stand in the
middle of the little close crammed with houses on the
site of the old apple orchard. Round the back of the
larger house built on the actual Ladbroke House site
there still seems to be some of the old ramshackle
garden and trees.
Went a short way up mill lane and then took the footpath
on the right leading on the edge of new house building to
straight lane. Here I picked up a glossy yellow
wild flower with its foliage for later indentification.
This turned out to be a Lesser Celandile or Pile Wort!
I felt a sense of jubilation at having begun to discover
a rich new world. Road side verges are no longer places
to ignore but rich wild habitats where wild flowers have
can grow undisturbed away from the managed farm fields.
Onward to Red Hills Lane
the right towards moor farm. This is one of those farms
where the location of footpaths has disappeared. I had
to walk straight across a sown field (not too bad at this
time of year
Arearef: the crop only knee high). When arriving at

Hillnumber: the farm buildings the route of the FP was blocked so had
to tramp round the back.
Now headed on the FP towards foster flatts farm looking for
a place to stop for lunch. There is an area of managed
grouse-rearing woodland between these two farms. I stopped
in a clearing-area to the left of the FP with some old
woodcutting equipment. This was a much nicer way to take
lunch than in some un-friendly dingy pub- warm
private with just the odd butterfly and squirrel for
company.
Off to foster flatts farm and strode boldly throught
the middle of the farm buildings though afterwards noticed
that the FP actually skirted them on the L.
On the track to the farm I noticed a large ash tree with
some of last year's keys so grabbed hold of a set. At this
point the farmer passed in his car looking rather bemused!
At the junction with Boroughbridge road
Roecliffe moor and explored an area of Beech woodland with
blue-bells just coming towards their peak. This path took
me to Copgrove then took the FP near the bridge into
Mountgarret estates land. I noticed this landowner has put
alot of effort into tree-planting. Many individual trees
often horse-chestnut have been planted along with whole
new woodland areas.
The path then followed the route of the beck and joins the
Ripon Rowel. The point at which the Rowel turns right there
is a T junction with a signpost and old boundary stone. I
placed a marker next to the E side of this stone as pretty
much the highest point of the day.
Just before I got to Stainley hall farm I notice to the R
of the FP an small patch of natural woodland. I peered
with and saw a magical scene like the Shire in the Spring-
a carpet of woodland flowers of all types. Couldnt resist
entering and standing in the stillness taking in this
wonderful scene. It had a feeling of natural enchantment.
The last excitement of the day was the only geocache in this
area at SE 30857 62992. Found it within seconds and left my
now customary calling card - Matt 13:44
Arearef: Wormal Green to South Stainley via Burton Leonard
Alt_Area: Wormald Green No 36 bus stop  -> South Stainley No 36 Bus Stop
Decided on this walk today because it offered some time in forest. I've really

Hillnumber: been into the autumn tints this year and have appreciated the beauty of this season
more than ever before. Missed out on a walk in the lakes at the weekend so
this was a bonus.
Started at the car park at fountains bridge with worship blasting away! I felt
a sense of urgency about the future today. It was a day to dream old dreams. A
day for a 'old man' to dream. Headed off into Spring Wood and began praying.
This urgency came on me about our call to the nations. It was a time to take
stock and I felt a need to plan a route to get there.
I entered a clearing in Spa Gill Woods. As I came into this area a real burden
came on me and had to stop
Arearef: bent and weeping. Oh I want to be there

Hillnumber: the leaves of the tree are for the healing of the nations. When I look back
at the end of my life I want to know that I have spent the best years of my life
serving the Lord in the nations. Later on I felt that I should pray that I will
be there on my 40th birthday. I want to give at least 20 years. In the clearing
there was a shooting hut/tree house which I climbed into and prayed.
[see photos 1&2]
The next day
Arearef: the next door neighbour george (aka. teshak) died suddenly of

Hillnumber: a heart attack. My cousin stephen had a stroke at the age of 36. I felt the
Lord impress on me the next day the scripture from psalm 90:12 "Teach
us to number our days aright that we may gain a heart of wisdom"
Its a time to really meditate on the promises
whatever steps the Lord leads to make those dreams a reality.
I was going to take the footpath from the middle section of Spa Gill
Wood towards Aldfield. But I was too busy praying and found myself
at the main road. A quick section dodging cars before I got to Moor
Lane [photo 3] which took me into the tidy village of Aldfield.
Across the fields after this towards the Obelisk sat comfortable
in fellowship with St Marys Church! Sat on the obelisk to enjoy a
coffee and the first dram of brandy from my hip flask!
Shortly afterwards
Arearef: on the footpath going towards Studley Roger

Hillnumber: I had the first of a number of close encounters with deer and
stags! I was quite daring approaching the stag. Read a sign later
saying that 'for your own safety' do not approach the deer because
it is rutting season!
Took a right turn towards the lake. Devils chimney was a bit eerie.
There were two or three little herds of deer each with a single stag.
These stags stood prominenlty on the steep sides in full view crying
out. This was presumably a variation on "come and have a go if you
think you're hard enough"
Once I got the fountains abbey boundary
in me and I bounded off up the steep forested valley side S of the
footpath in search of a real close encounter with a stag. I realised later
that this was quite a moronic thing to do because I had just passed
the fountains abbey boundary which had an enormous high iron
fence which was clearly there to keep the deer in..
Anyway I was soon glad that I had 'offroaded' as I was just out of
sight when I heard this strange humming sound coming W along
the valley. The humming turned into a hubbub and soon an
enormous party of prattling pensioners filed past underneath me.
I'm sure all the stags had run for cover before they got a chance
to stand en-masse and gawp.
Finally hit the footpath again at the corner of Macjershaw Trough
and headed W
There was an amusing incident at Hill House Farm. I arrived just
behind a farm workers quad-bike and closed the field gate for him.
A dog ran off barking behind him which would otherwise have been
interested in me. Just as I was leaving the farm area it realised there
was an unwelcome guest and decided on a bit of intimidation. I
feigned indifference as it barked at my legs and made it to the
far gate with no chunks missing. I then saw a party of 4 middle
aged walkers 100 yards away standing looking at their maps. I
mischeivous thought occurred to me to warn them off a ravenous
dog and cut short their walk! I had though better of it and was in
the process of walking past when this polite lady asked me whether
the footpath went through the farm. "Yes
right of those farm buildings and past the nasty dog" "Oh
she replied.
I went my way. This clearly had the desired effect. I looked back
a couple times and they were still there a couple of minutes later
trying to pluck up sufficient courage to face cerberus. That done
there was still time to take a little detour into the woods to the
W of Robin Hoods Well and have a peek at the abbey through
the trees.

This may have been the longest  walk I have ever done.
And I needed the time away. I  realised early on in the
walk that I have not for some  time been listening to
my heart.
But as I did this now I  realised how tough
its been this year. There has  been the worry over Linda's
health and the stress that has  caused us. The laying down of
my desire for a second child  was hard and made more so as I
invested much in the Russian  adoption. I realised that
I have given myself little  time to work through the real
grieving process. I have known  much defeat this year in
the area of impurity as these  pressures have come to bear. As I
walked I saw an inward picture  of myself walking on
with a grimace of pain
Arearef: not  looking up but looking at my feet.

We  are preparing increasingly to go into mission
in the  battle and in need of new strength as I face the  beginning of the
biggest spiritual battle of  my life  for lives of those in the country of blessing.
I was encouraged to  remember how God restored me then and used me
powerfully in Guinea Bissau and  asked Him to do it again.
I  felt the Lord saying that I need to go at my own pace with Him and not

If  anything which comes out of this place of rest will be characterised by grace.

Great conditions for this walk in mid-may! Started off

Hillnumber: in shorts and tea shirt. The only downside was that it was quite hazy so could
only see mid-distance. Sunshine all day. Thought on good-friday in these conditions that I would
have to choose an out-of-the-way place to avoid the crowds. Half the population
of the UK had the same idea. Haweswater car park holds about 15 cars. When
I arrived at 11am cars were parked back from there for about 600M!
People were arriving all the time. Ah well I decided to accept the crowds and
started towards Small water. Wasnt easy to pray trying to keep people
ahead and behind out of ear-shot!
By the time I reached Small water I was longing to
'off-road'. There were walkers behind every rock and crevice. Decided to avoid the
motorway to Nan Bield Pass and go up the East ridge of Mardale Ill
Bell.
As I struck off on my own there was the opportunity to wave at one
walker sidling off behind a large boulder for an obvious purpose. He waved back!
At last I was able to enjoy the fell and talk to the Lord about wanting
to live in the Spirit. "In his presence are pleasures forever more and
fullness of joy"- nothing the world offers compares.
Had lunch halfway up the E ridge where I found a triangular stone and
decided on the format of my "marker": Stand at the E side of the cairn
Walk 5 paces E
Arearef: place triangular stone here pointing E

Hillnumber: underside of the stone with a cross.
Struck up the virtually non-existent E ridge to hit the summit exactly.
Surprisingly I had it to myself (for a few minutes) and placed my first
marker! Now I began the time-trial: Could I get to kidsty pike
and be back at  the car at 3:15? Set off at top-speed towards High Street. In 20 mins
I was there. My dodgy hip wasnt getting in the way much. Just time to
leave a marker and move on my way to Kidsty Pike. Scenery around the
straits of Riggindale was awesome. Reached Kidsty Pike in 25 mins. View
of high street fells was great from the summit. I dont find summits are
great places to linger when there is a crowd :-( Off on another romp again taking a
short cut from the crowds to the S of Kidsty Howes. Detoured round the Rigg finally and back for 3:35pm

Today I did a great walk - the dovedale horseshoe (with
Middle Dodd and Red Screes) and two think I will remember which I felt
God say:
1. I need to develop a "rythm of running"- to settle
into a running rythm for the long haul. Speaking of spiritual
consistency and reminding me again of the daily discipline.
2. The wind was gale force NE - biting cold. As I looked
over at Little Hart Crag I felt the Lord say to me "find a cleft in the
rock". I could see a place and climbed up and nestled in it to have my
lunch. This was a haven of Spring in the midst of Winter - a true
almost miraculous calm in the storm! I could no longer hear the wind
howling but only the melting of icicles. And I felt the Lord remind me
of the prophecy "..you are literally seeing the hand of God coming and
pushing you inside of Jesus -you are going to be hidden in Him.." Also
was reminded of Ex 34:22 "when my glory passes by I will put you in a
cleft in a rock and cover you with my hand" Then I felt the picture of
Jesus asleep in the boat come to me. This is speaking to me of coming
to a really powerful place in my life literally being hidden in God
living in Him
Arearef: in His holiness. This is the secret place of the Most

Hillnumber: High where one rests secure in the midst of any storm
elements of the world. The secret place of holiness
Him - a walk of His life lived out in His holiness and my life hidden
within. And this is not just a hiding
Arearef: but a joining - I am joined to

Hillnumber: Him
Arearef: one with His life of power and holiness and this becomes the

Hillnumber: nature of the life that is lived.
Other memories of the walk:
Sunrise over Gray Crag.
Joy on Middle Dodd.
Marker on Red Screes was placed partially under an overhanging stone -the rock above marked with a + symbol.
Scandale Tarn was beautiful.
Marker on Dove Crag was probably a little loose as the ground was frozen so couldn't bed it in.
Ground on Hart Crag was frozen and snow covered so no chance of leaving marker there.
Hart Crag was Wild! Really felt the need of crampons as the snow was compacted and slippery. Had the
presence of mind to mark a waypoint at NY 37060 10870 just before the
final ascent of Hart Crag as this would leave a safer route to
Hartsop-above-How if the direct route off rocky Hart Crag proved a bad
idea. Chose to return here rather than taking the direct route off the
summit. Gale force NE winds
the summit meant that this was the only sensible option. So I set the
GPS to navigate me back to this waypoint.. I had quickly become
disorientated in the snow
Arearef: mist and wind and the GPS was pointing to a

Hillnumber: direction very different from my "internal compass"!
Descended off the summit to meet a group of what must
have been 50+ people who had skipped the summit on their way round the
fairfield horseshoe. This heightened my sense of acheivement!
Cut across onto the Hartsop-above-How ridge from the
safety waypoint.
Stood on High Bakestones at about 1.15pm aware of a
change in the weather coming inexorably from the NE. From 1pm when the
bank of weather was first spotted over High Street in bright sunshine
1.25pm saw High Street in mist. It was 5 mins after this that I found
myself also in mist on the summit of Dove Crag. The deterioration was
complete when driving snow arrived on the summit of Hart Crag at 2mp.

Hillnumber: The trek to the campsite was the fun bit. Maybe that says alot! We had to wait for Ross to escape the demands of home so arrived at Kentmere Church at 9:15pm faced with a yomp up Kentmere. We would have to cover 6.5km before nightfall. It proved impossible
Arearef: particularly with heavy rucksacks. My "world" rucksack was dusted down  after a 6 year break since its last adventure in Guyana - still displaying amazonian dirt.

Hillnumber: The light finally failed as we were skirting round Kentmere Reservoir. For the next 30 mins we relied on petzl headlamps. My GPS battery failed at the crucial point
Arearef: leaving us relying on Ross's mountain leadership ( ' ML' ) skills. Using bearings
Alt_Area: speed and timings we navigated right onto our desired spot. Not having had a great chance to look at the location

Hillnumber: I think we missed out on the major plusses for me of camping - seeing a mountain sunset and sunrise
from the mountain. Next morning

Hillnumber: porch for a view down the valley
Arearef: we'd pitched right behind a stone wall!

Hillnumber: Up went the tent with great efficiency. Ross tried to not make too much of his blow-up sleeping mat after this. I had the faint sense of injustice that he was "cheating"! He seemed to sleep like a log. I must have struggled to get 3 hours of light sleep. The dawn chorus was more a dawn solo by a bird which seemed to have taken a great interest our interoping tent. Either that or it was just having a laugh! It warbled 4 inches away from my ear outside the tent!
Up we got and the day now began to resemble a Duke of Edinburgh expedition. Packed up our tent. A quick breakfast of weetabix in a tupperware container and we were off by 9am.
Time and again
Arearef: Ross forged ahead pushing the pace for no apparent reason other than a need to get back on time under pain of death.

Hillnumber: We headed straight up the side of a stream towards a gully leading to Thorthwaite Crag
Arearef: a route wainwright described as "tedious". Here Ross began his habit of forging ahead resulting in the irritating scenario of him taking regular breaks waiting for me to catch up
Alt_Area: while I could take none. Add to this the drenching drizzle rain
AreaLinkID: cloud down to 1000' and a heavy rucksack continually seeking to pull me off the slope - this was a real hard slog.

Hillnumber: Once on the 1000' ascent to the gully
Arearef: Ross suggested I go in front to set the pace. This I did gladly but found that within 5 minutes I had once been instructed on the path ahead
Alt_Area: and had found him forging ahead again. Here I can only assume that the pace I set was not going to keep us on schedule.

Hillnumber: Thornthwaite Crag was reached by 10:10am
Arearef: the beacon looming suddenly out of the mist. It was here that my camera signed its own death warrant. It obstinately refused to take a picture of the summit in the light conditions.

Hillnumber: Ross got his camera out and it performed immediately. A digital camera is now top of my required item list.

We now began the forced march to Froswick. Here we paused only briefly before picking up the pace again towards Ill Bell. The pace seemed to relax somewhat after this. Our time on Ill Bell was for me the highlight of the walk.
That morning I had asked the Lord to break the cloud when we were on Ill Bell summit. As we approached Ill Bell I had real sense of anticipation
Arearef: so strong in fact that I could almost have said to Ross 'wait here until the cloud breaks'.

Hillnumber: And so it did. A shout of excitement came from another walker on the summit as the cloud suddenly

broke to reveal the valley. Other sections of the cloud continued to break revealing views culminating in a hole in the sky being seemingly almost punched above us allowing sunlight to bathe the summit.
At this point I told Ross about the prayer - I couldn't keep it to myself!
We enjoyed another dose of hot chocolate using Ross's impressive stove and then set off towards Yoke.

We chose a lunch stop in the dip between Ill Bell and Yoke. Apparently insects gather more on summits due to the presence of discarded food .We had a chat about how to make sure that we didnt increasingly play "spiritually safe" as we got older
Arearef: particularly if we get hurt on the cutting edge. We did have a good time together.

Hillnumber: On to Yoke which was in cloud and back to Garburn Pass and Kentmere church
I came out of this experience physically and emotionally drained and felt the effects of this for a week afterwards. My time away is so precious
Arearef: time when I am alone with God and He renewes my strength and vision. It was hard to drive past Kendal
Alt_Area: and the Worm Boot Shop without feeling acutely that this is what I really need at this time.

Decided that it was high time I got to know the mountains and valleys closest to kendal better.

Hillnumber: Started the day with a plan A and plan B. Plan A was to climb Kentmere Pike via Steel Rigg and
then loop round to Gatescarth pass taking Harter Fell on the way. Plan B was Sallows and Sour
Howes if the weather was bad.
By the time the final decision was made I was onto about
plan G! Parked at Sad Gill in sunshine but was dissappointed to see
that there was mist at about 2000' at the head of Longsleddale. I was
glad to get anything in today really with worries about my left eye being up to it. But it
greatly improved on Sunday. A pulled muscle in my right leg was nearly
right but there was a doubt over how it would stand up to a big walk.
In the event it wasnt a problem.
Started off up Sad Gill talking to the Lord about the future. A break in the pressure of work
has given me time to think more about our long term plans. It has though been difficult so far this
year to keep focused and free from fear as worries about the eye have persisted. It is a real
battle against fear. It's been encouraging to see how Linda has seen a real breakthrough in
this area recently and has supported me to overcome the giant of fear in my own life.
She also felt God say recently that promises about missions place us in the shoes of
Abraham who was strengthened in faith and gave glory to God because he believed the
promises even though he knew his body was as good as dead. That is our position - in the
natural going as a family into mission is so out of the pattern of our lives right now.
But we must believe and encourage ourselves in the promises also. This confirmed
just what God had said to me after emily arrived. I am living now in the
fulfillment of all Gods promises of being married and being a Father. I inherited
those promises by faith. Now I must do the same with the second great
faith challenge of my life - our calling to mission.
Today became an example of the life of walking by faith
and an encouragement that to those who trust
promises. That seasons change quickly
Arearef: like dry river beds in the Negev suddenly filled with

Hillnumber: water.
Walking up Backbarrow Crag I thought I remembered reading in Wainwright that the Steel Rigg
route should not be attempted in mist. A quick check confirmed this. Plan C was then hatched -
Tarn Crag and Grey Crag on the other side of Longsleddale were as yet clear of mist. Climb them starting a
Brownhowe Bottom.
As I climbed towards this I began thinking that with all the time I had
accomplished. So Plan D became Plan C plus branstree
Arearef: going E from the head of Gatescarth pass.

Hillnumber: I was walking along the gatescarth pass byway above Wren Gill when the weather suddenly closed in.
In the space of 5 minutes
Arearef: from being able to see all of the East side of Longsleddale

Hillnumber: and the enclosed valley
Arearef: I was in mist and the only familiar feature was the byway! As wainwright

Hillnumber: warned against Tarn Crag in mist
Arearef: plans C and D were dead!

Hillnumber: Enter plans E
Plan E was to follow the line of the fence E from the head of Gatescarth Pass to Branstree and retrace my steps.
Plan F was to follow the fence W of this point taking in Adam Seat and Harter Fell then retracing steps.
Plan G was plan F but continue after Harter Fell along the fence and take in Kentmere Pike and Shipman Knotts.
I arrived at the pass. The wind was whistling past with a fearful windchill. I took a deep breath and
headed W towards Adam Seat. This is where I began to walk by faith! The conditions were nasty. Ice had formed in
the direction of the wind on any obstacle in its path. There were some wierd
formations on the wire fence and tall grass. I soon had to protect myself as much as possible from the
wind with the kagool leaving just a small gap through which to see.
I relied for peace of mind on the compass and map
referring to them often. Arriving at what I thought was adams
seat I was saw on the map the symbol BS. Had some fun opening
up the map to find the meaning of this symbol - Boundary Stone. Sure
enough there was an ancient erect stone on which was carved the symbol
'L'. Continued up towards Harter Fell passing through some snow fields.
Came across the first wierd cairn of Harter Fell with its nightmarish quality. Pressed on towards
Harter Fell encouraged by another correctly located Boundary Stone
this time inscribed with an 'L'
After stopping briefly at the summit of Harter Fell I decided to go for Plan G! It was a long walk
along the top towards what I knew should be kentmere pike. I had soon lost my sense of direction
relying on the compass completely
Arearef: checking regularly that I was on track by

Hillnumber: confirming that the fence was swinging round towards a SE direction. Still after so
long relying entirely on the map and compass
Fear grows even though you're sure that
right on course. I was a relieved when the ground began to swell again
presumably towards Kentmere Pike summit. The cairn and OS column
confirmed that I was still OK.
Just before reaching the summit I had a short sense that
the gloom had brightened a little. I stopped dead and wheeled
round to where I thought the light was and thought I could detect something. This
happended a few times.
Settled down to lunch on Kentmere Pike. It happened again - a chink of
light in the howling gloom! Then a definite white path came and went.
Suddenly a bright expanse of sky appeared...I jumped up. In a few
moments an awesome vista opened up - a caught a glimpse of a mountain
ridge on the other side of the wall and began to shout for joy! The mist then
broke into ribbons and all was revealed. It happened so fast...
It took me a while to orientate myself. What I initially
thought was ullswater or thirlmere I realised was Windermere. The range
I first saw was the Western side of Kentemere - Yoke
Finally I set off towards Shipman Knotts in sunshine.
Took a quick detour to Goat scar to inspect it after its foreboding
display this morning. On shipman Knotts I decided to build a better cairn. Hopefully cleared up
a bit of confusion by removing a large stone from the southern most grassy knoll
and placing it on the middle (highest) one.
Back down to Sadgill via Sadgill wood where I lingered for a while before crossing
the bridge over the Sprint. To my delight as I did this
first drops of rain began to fall!
Footnote 8 November 2009:
We are moving onto lifes plan C after seeing the "second great
faith challenge of my life - our calling to mission" not work out due
to the mess of WEC Senegal. Might life's journey end up at Plan G?

Hillnumber: Up in kendal for a weekend with emily I was planning
when I could squeeze a walk in but Mum second guessed
and had one of her good ideas- why not walk through
the gap and be picked up in Glenridding. I bit her hand
off but planned to make a slight diversion to Seat Sandal.
As I was set down at Mill Bridge
me an extra half-hour and I had four hours and ten minutes
to do the walk instead of the 3.5 hours bernard takes.
So off I went straight up the side of Seat Sandal I have
looked at dozens of times from grasmere. The weather was
a treat as well
no mist and only a few drops of rain.
I needed this break to get thinking clearly again. There
is so much (too much) pressure on at home and I have
really felt the need of a break for some time. Yet I'm
aware that 4 hours isnt really enough. Talking to Pete
yesterday- he has a yearly retreat to the Lakes for 3/4
days and on the first day he often finds his head is
still buzzing with all the life of home. I think I
was in that place really still at the end of the walk -
refreshed but not really fully back on track.
I felt what God was emphasising was that I must press
in will all energy to lay hold of that for which Christ
Jesus laid hold of me. I came to Him first with the
heart cry I just want to be free and His response was
lay hold of me and you will be free indeed. There
was a burden to press in to experience the glorious
liberation of the children of God. It is not Gods
heart that I merely control the flesh but that I
put on Christ. I am in a battle of deliverance at
present and must press through.
I met a total of two people on Seat Sandal and am
convinced that the sparcity of people was partly
due to today Cup Final! I had the summit all to
myself and placed the marker (Note 5 paces from
estimated centre of cairn) before descending
steeply to grizedale tarn where I joined the
relative A road of traffic. Though in truth there
were still few people about it was enough to make
me seek refuge by walking down grizedale on the
opposite side to the main path.
By the time I reached the place where a path crosses
over the stream I was up against the clock and
yomped the last 45 minutes. Raced up to lanty's
tarn it coming into view at exactly 4 o'clock
(the agreed meeting time).
The last treat of the day was walking through the
sea of bluebells in flower on the fell side taking
their turn of prominence before the bracken overshadowed
them for the rest of the summer.
Joined a Pendlebury family tradition of a pot of tea
at the Greystones Cafe in Glenridding. It was great
to walk down the final stretch into Glenridding and
see emily in the distance walking along the stream

Alt_Area: My second stab at an eXtreme lakes experience! This one

Hillnumber: a little wilder than the Kentmere camp. As we approached the weekend
the weather forecast was littered with severe weather warnings and
things looked pretty nasty.
Still we decided it was now or much later so went ahead
with a slightly less ambitious plan of finding a campsite just off the
floor or the Langdale valley. Plan A had been to drive up to Hardknott pass
and camp half-way up Cold Pike.
The moment we came when I stepped out of the warm car at
the head of Langdale and set my face to complete this challenge. I knew
it was going to be a rough experience
myself for this I felt some exhiliration as we strode off into the
darkness in search of our site. Almost immediately
Caradhras was set against us. The wind got up and hail was in our
faces.
Strode through Stool End (lovely name) and past the
farmer who simply ignored us and up towards "the Band". Ross's plan was
to look for a campsite just above the little wooded area hear the
intake wall. We skirted around the top of this area but found it to be
fairly sloping. One area just inside the wood was flat but too
rocky. So retraced our steps to a site we'd passed up previously as
being a little sloping and settled for this as the best
available option.
Up went the tent. I was not getting fairly cold with the
wind chill and was glad to get in. The night was a repeat of the
Kentmere camp with Ross sleeping soundly. I spent most of the night
trying not to roll on top of him. In the middle of the night we were distured by a
sheep who seemed equally disturbed that we were there. It
was bleeting in a most distressed manner just outside the tent and
seemed to be asking permission to join us inside. It
finally gave up. Next morning there was a lone sheep lingering around
the camp area - probably the same one!
The weather was no better the next day. In fact the rain
was persistent throughout the entire period of the expedition! We
decided against the Crinkles as we could see that snow was lying at high level.
The days' target was Pike O' Blisco which was destined to become the first Wainwright to have been climbed three times. It
reached that distinction throught the chance decisions of  others rather than the direction of my own will.
We'd just got going
Beck when we stopped for 20 minutes for the absolute necessity of
taking water from the Beck
Arearef: boiling it and storing it in a container.

Hillnumber: The 1.5 litres of water which I had was ample for both of  us in
reality. He does take this ML stuff rather seriously at times.
There was an ongoing
Arearef: unspoken tension between us in the

Hillnumber: matter of altitude readings which simmered away through the whole
time and came to a head on the summit! Ross had brought his new
pride and joy - a flash (mechanical) barometer/altimeter! On numerous
occasions he would study it and then state sagely that the
pressure was doing this and that so the weather would do this and that
at some unspecified time in the future. The altitude
would also be read out with the confidence of one stating immutable
fact. However this immutable fact didnt always get as close
as my GPS to the OS MAP altitude. The acid test
what the two rivals would tell us on the summit of Pike
O'Blisco
We raced up the mountain. Ross seems to like treating
climbing as aerobic exercise
atitude is somewhat different. If I break out into a sweat
look for an appropriately flat rock
result of our contrasting approaches is the repeatedly Ross strikes out
ahead
Arearef: I plod along losing ground to him
Alt_Area: he stops to wait for me then

Hillnumber: sets off again when I catch up. Groundhog day starring the

From this point on
Arearef: the walk became eXtreme. The path

Hillnumber: off the summit we took headed in the direction of Bleaberry Knott
initially and took us
10-12 rock climbing pitches. I've never had to do anything like this in the lakes
before. I guess its a route that didnt even get into
Wainwright. Clear route it was though. Add the falling snow
and 30 mph winds and this was no walk-in-the-park. Ross went
down the first pitch putting his rock climbing skills into practice and
then guided me down. I didnt feel particularly
comfortable
Arearef: mostly because I was doing this with my pack on and felt

Hillnumber: it was pulling me off. I guess it puts the failure of Puig
Caragoler to bed though. The next pitch was easier as I handed my
rucksack to Ross before going down.
Things were back to sane lakeland standard after that.
We yomped the rest of the path down Redacre Gill
on the horrible rock staircase. I must admit to really disliking
these constructions. They are really hard work on the legs and give the
walk a monotonous plodding sort of feeling.On my own
I may have avoided the steps entirely and 'Off-Roaded'. We both
abandoned them anyway after having slipped - ice
had formed dangerously on them.
The challenge was over. Back into the air conditioned
car. I'm more convinced than ever that camping and rain dont
go together. It was fun
recharge batteries but rather to run them down.

Hillnumber: Map of intended route (pink) and actual track (yellow) from EasyGPS.
Chose to escape the crowds if such a thing was possible on Bank Holiday Monday
in the Lake District! The most out-of-the-way valley - Ennerdale. Not only
that but the least frequented walk from there.
And
Alt_Area: it is out-of-the-way. Driving from Kendal at top speed

Hillnumber: clear roads in the early morning
Arearef: it still took me 1 hour and 40 minutes to

Hillnumber: arrive at the Broadmoor car park. I was weary from the drive upon arrival
and felt I needed a break before the walk began. I was also somewhat
deflated to see a stream of gaitered walkers walking along the road to the
lake.
I found it rather strange at the time that all these people seemed to be
walking along the road rather than driving to the car park and starting
the walk from there. I realised afterwards that these people were very
likely to be doing the coast-to-coast walk. The first two days of this
according the AQ book are:
Day 1
Travel to St Bees for your first night's accommodation Miles Km
Day 2
St Bees to Ennerdale Bridge 14 22
So if people travelled up on Saturday (as is likely) they would arrived
en-masse at Ennerdale at about 9:30 am on Monday morning having just
scoffed their Full English in a B&B somewhere near Ennerdale Bridge.
Imagine it - 2 weeks when you keep bumping into the same people. You'd
have to approach it as a "get to know you" excercise or it would drive you
mad!
So my enthusiasm for a Big Walk was fairly low. I have realised that it is
not walking itself which I enjoy
Arearef: but walking with God. I felt really that I

Hillnumber: did the main business with God on Blubberhouses on Friday. Perhaps I need to
regain a deeper level of intimacy with God so that three days alone with
Him can be filled.
I did manage to escape the crowds by heading straight up Grike on a FP
neither on the map nor in AW. (Through a conifer plantation due to be
felled soon). As I walked up this I started to pray about Tanzania and
mission and didnt feel that I was getting anywhere until I felt God was
changing my focus. Instead of looking for a big "Yes - there" he spoke to
me about finding my fulfillment in him not in what I do - but in being a
friend of God. I realised that I had begun to equate personal fulfillment
with being in the right place and doing the right things. These in
themselves are not wrong
Arearef: but my soul must find rest in God alone.

Hillnumber: Approaching Grike I saw to my horror that even in this most unlikely
place there was a couple just approacing the summit. I turned round and
found a quiet spot out of sight of the summit and waited there. Looking
behind I could see that I was being watched from the brow near the summit!
Yet actually if you studied visitors to Grike over a year period
on Bank Holiday Monday in August would one of a handful of busiest moments
in the whole year on this spot.. Yet I am constrained to do things at the
same time as everyone else. I look for the feeling of being off the well-
beaten track  - but here I was taking my place in the queue for the summit.
It negates much of the sense of wildness and exploration that I come to
a place like Ennerdale to find.
After these intrusions though
Arearef: I saw few people for the rest of the

Hillnumber: day. The same couple were just leaving calf crag on my arrival there.
I picked up a "oh no its that wierd bloke on his own" vibe so I gave them
a jovial wave which they were obliged to mirror back to me.
Then the long trudge over Iron Crag (the summit of which was beyond me due
to a wall fortified with quadruple barbed wire. This I later discover had
recently been strengthened to protect sheep grazing of the "Side" to encourage
the ancient forest there to spread). After this I decided to make my way
down to the valley avoiding Caw Fell et al. I was glad of this as it enabled
me to enjoy the highlight of the walk at a slower pace- the Ennerdale Water
and the remnant of the ancient forest on the Side. This was a delight in
the evening sunshine
Arearef: reminding me of my previous evening introduction to

Hillnumber: Ennerdale on the other side of the lake when I had mistakenly tried to
meet up with Mary at Ennerdale YHA rather than Elterwater YHA - and
stayed with Bob Orrell at his farmhouse.
Ennerdale is marred by the enormous conifer plantations planted after the
1st world war. There is an attempt to reverse this in the "Wild Ennerdale
Project" See http://www.wildennerdale.co.uk
I sent them the following email:
Rachel
I was in Ennerdale over the weekend and was
very impressed with the work which has been
done in the valley. I'm glad to see that
future plans include tackling to ugliness of
the monoculture conifer plantations which
mar the vally.
However I would ask that a more interventionist
approach is taken to deal with the impact of
the large areas of conifer in the valley. I
believe that the temporary impact of felling
machinery and the visual impact of clearfell
areas would be outweighed by the longer term results
which this would provide. Could clear felling
be speeded up and increased in these areas together
with planting of native tree seedlings? Seed/
seedlings from the ancient woodland areas on
the South shore of Ennerdale water could perhaps
be used to some extent?
Regards

the north the rain had begun again in earnest. After having negociated
the hairpins on the shoulder of hallin fell I realised that I'd left

I'm glad I did carry on as I really enjoyed this walk
even though most of it was done in rain or light snow
of the mist. I had a good time with God as we talked about gipton. He
reassured me that I should not search my own heart if it fails because
He's pleased about my obedience. The views were not panoramic maybe
but they were awesome in a different way. Across boardale all I could
see was the rising slopes of Place Fell
green to white as they rose and merged with the mist
of the massive fell above. Across martindale
similar grand impression. And there was little Pike-a-wassa which I
climbed with Pete not really knowing where I was in the lakes.
On top of Winter crag I disturbed two swooping birds of
prey
Arearef: all black with flayed pronged tails. I later was told they were

Hillnumber: only ravens!
On past Winter Crag and the rain turned to light snow.
Much preferable as its not wet
Arearef: and therefore not as cold. It was

Hillnumber: fairly pleasant on top of Beda fell where I had a little time to pray
more. Walking on the high ground of the fells seems a natural place to
talk to the Lord about how things are going and look at the big picture
of what is ahead. It reminds me also of the scripture which is
important to me at the moment "He makes my feet like the feet of a
deer
Arearef: he enables me to walk on my High Places". I'm reminded to always

Hillnumber: be hungry to do that.

Hillnumber: Up in kendal for a long weekend. According to the
forecast  for this weekend
Arearef: several new lakes were likely to form.

Hillnumber: I'd almost given up hope of the rain stopping when there
was an unscheduled break midday on sunday.
Linda was nice about me disappearing and by 2:10 I was
parked up at Lesketh How just past Ambleside (no room at
the inn)
It was a lovely early winter scene which developed as I
climbed out of ambleside towards High Sweden Bridge. The
sun soon disappeared but the lack of rain seemed miraculous
enough!
I followed Scandale Beck up through a section of ancient
forest hugging its' gorge. Once High Sweden bridge was
crossed I felt like I was 'on the fells'. Had a good prayer
time in the early part of the walk before time-pressure
cut in. Feel like I'm back on track in terms of intercession
since during the major battle of Aug-Nov 2002 saw me get out
of the habit.
After taking the first part of the walk at a easy pace
realised  I'd have to push it to get to my objective. This is where my
delusions began about the identity of Low Pike. I assumed it
was the obvious peak above me as AW descrived it as the 'first
prominent peak seen from the streets of ambleside'. In fact
I was struggling to climb High Pike with only 1hour ascent
time from Lesketh How!
The time factor became more focused by a man coming
down with his two daughters. He clearly thought I was off my
rocker and didnt seem relieved that I was only ascending Low
Pike! His daughter wished me 'good luck' as we parted! After
this I did a bit of fell running through the marshy hollows.
So I reached a peak at 3pm assuming it to be high brock
crags. Looked at the watch and was getting really disappointed that
I just didnt quite have the time to reach Low Pike.
Began to come to my senses when looking at the map and seeing
the pattern of the stone walls on the red screes side of scandale
beck seemed to indicate that I was near Low Pike. Turned to AW
and the drawing of High Pike from Low pike was a clincher!
After a quick stop on the summit to admire my twice
unexpected acheivement
Arearef: turned for home. First spots of rain hit my face

Hillnumber: like bullets as I did so. Declared to caradhras that I had
triumphed and she could throw whatever she desired at me in her
anger.
Excitement on the way down was swinging off a branch to
negociate the last part of High Brock crags (near the Rock Step). Back at
the car in the dark for 3:50pm

Hillnumber: Since returning to Methley Grove in early September
Arearef: there was an initial buzz from being in a familiar environment. Latterly though I am still aware of a real sense of not being at rest. I am questioning what is the right setting for us to really feel new. The Lord is the one who renews
AreaLinkID: so I am seeking Him over this. So the questions are - "Is Methley Grove a place to stay for the next few years?" "Is Leeds".

AreaLinkID: to a whole heart serving the Lord wholeheartedly? It is important also not to just go with the obvious road

Hillnumber: I mused much on this today. On our decision to come to Leeds last year. Then

As seems to happen often at the moment
quite down emotionally and spiritually. Emily has not been sleeping
through and Linda's cold persists. I dont seem to have the energy
to get out of the valley and it was this walk which gave me the
hope to climb out again. I almost felt it was happening literally
as I climbed up from Limefitt park.
I lift up my eyes to the hills-
where does my help come from?
2 My help comes from the LORD
the Maker of heaven and earth.
This so often happens and is why I love to walk alone. Though I
know that there is a great difference between loneliness and solitude.
Solitude is being alone with God and I find that solitude in the
mountains.
Parked in the layby just short of Limefitt park campsite/caravan park which
was heaving. It even has a pub! Soon left the crowds behind huddled in
their tents and struck directly for applethwaite quarry with its strange
viewing platforms. After negotiating a couple of barbed wire fences I was

This day started out sounding like a walking day on a

Hillnumber: methodist  guild holiday! The A party were heading for Dove Crag via Dovedale.
B party going up Blea Rigg. The pathetic C party were scaling Black
Crag.
I joined the C party after seeing the low cloud level. Fancied a walk
through some forest round Skelwith Bridge.
Parked at the Jorysz hotel a.k.a. Skelwith Bridge hotel.
This walk was a game of two halves. First half was a leisurely (prayerful) walk
skirting the edge of Black crag on two sides. The second half was
a frenzied attempt to get back to the car by 12:30. Not much prayer
took place on the second half but it was fun.
First Half: 09:45 -11:10
Over skelwith bridge. Nursed throught the only finding of the footpath
towards Colwith force (the first footpath sign said "If you're looking
for the footpath to Colwith Force its 100 yards further up the road"
in about that many words!)
Crossed over the minor road to Elterwater and enjoyed walking through
the forest towards the charmingly named "Little Fell" - dappled sun
on brand new bright green beech leaves. Down the lane SE towards the
coniston road. It was about this time that I realised I didnt have
much time to complete the walk. I was faced with the definate prospect
of failing to acheive the 1026' of Black Crag! The rest was a Yomp...
Second Half: 11:10
No time to look at the map. Navigation mistake soon followed. took the
road to Oxen Fell at the junction. Took the next turn correctly and
was soon yomping up towards the Iron Keld plantation. I split the
second half into two 40 minute sections with the summit of Black crag
in the middle at 11:50. By the time I got into the Iron Keld plantation
I realised this wasnt on but was quite enjoying the speed. Left a
couple of overweight middle-aged walkers in my wake. Reached the summit
huffing and puffing at 12:00 and placed a marker.
Now the only way to get to the car for 12:30 was the direct route N
over the feel. Ignored the sign saying access was only to a viewpoint
N and off I went. Some fell running was required while stuffing
sandwiches  in my face. Tried to keep N but the will of the mountain 'turned me
ever Westwards' and I found myself at barbed wire fence at the squiggly
start of the C road at the western end of park fell. Sprinted the final
100M in a time of 9:89 seconds to reach the car at 12:45

Hillnumber: After the first successful pre-breakfast walk from Kendal
I decided to tackle something just a little bigger. And with
my new-found interest in Birketts
The media was insisting on severe weather over the new
year period. New years eve was supposed to have severe gales
and rain! And getting up in the dark I could hear the rain
beating on the window. I decided to go for it anyway and
was rewarded!
The weather on the ascent was "squally" - showers could be
seen approaching over from the stavely area giving time for
waterproofs to be on before the rain began.
I was given a treat on the summit as the weather cleared
all around
Arearef: finally bathing me in sunshine. The gray-green of

Hillnumber: the ascent changed into the most beautifully verdant green of
morning sunlight on the fields below the Knott.
I felt the Lord calling me once again to intimacy with me
to take delight in friendship with Him. As the door to the
nations opens and effective service beckons
always be my first delight. I must always seek His face
just delight in service.

Hillnumber: Staying at Seathwaite Lodge for a weekend of walking just after we got the health go-ahead
for Linda for us to go to Senegal.
Day started after a good English breakfast at the tradition start time of 9:30 ish. Bright sunshine in
Dunnerdale was not to last as a bank of cloud advanced visiblly from the SW turning light blue into
dull grey.
By the time the final ascent of the Walna Scar pass was being made
Arearef: the scene resembled more a mountaineering

Hillnumber: expedition as the track led upwards into a dull grey snowfield. At the pass
coming up from Coniston
Arearef: but turning away to Walna Scar summit I was largely alone again except for a keen

Hillnumber: bagger or two adding a couple of extras to their days haul on the main Coniston Massif.
Here on top in the snow surrounding Walna Scar summit
a snack and coffee here in a calm unexpected for a fell top in January. Shortly though after this break
day turned into more of a mountaineering challenge as mist descended
Arearef: obscuring the route from White Maiden to

Hillnumber: White Pike. And I was thrown back onto my raw skills
Arearef: my GPS not having the waypoints for these two. I first

Hillnumber: chose to follow the snow prints of the bagger but realised after a while that he may be heading first for
White Pike. Then trusting to my compass skills I navigated well from White Maiden using the wall as an
excellent guide.
The trickiest section of the walk was now ahead- the section from White Pike to Pikes
any guidebook. I chose a route almost due south to avoid what looked on the map to be some buttresses to the
SW of White Pike's summit. I chose this route well and wove my way down though a steep trough with these
buttresses appearing to my right. Going was not easy due to the melting snow. Made quick progress to Pikes
which was probably my favourite peak of the day. An unfrequented place like this gives an impression that
today Pikes belonged to me - the hill waited patiently for my arrival in the afternoon and then returned to its
solitude on my departure. On leaving the top though I was sorely tempted by the mass of Caw dominating the view.
Caw had avoided my grasp once yesterday
Arearef: just out of range of the day's expedition. I was faced with the same

Hillnumber: goading mountain today. Was there enough daylight left to conquer it? After enjoying my rest on Pikes I was r
eady for a dash up caw and 28 minutes after leaving Pikes I was standing exultant on Caw
revenge with her slippery summit rocks. The GPS did well to come out unharmed from its 10 foot plunge off
the summit rocks onto the grass below!
There was now only time for a direct descent off Caw towards Seathwaite before the light failed.
Markers left:
Walna Scar
White Maiden
White Pike
Pikes
Caw

First full day of my escape to Snowdonia was a relaxed affair after the long drive after work yesterday.

Hillnumber: The morning was spent resting at the Pen-y-Gwyrd hotel with the rain lashing the windows. Partly in the spartan room (mine was Crib Goch) and partly in the Panneled bar area in front of a roaring fire with all the celeb signatures on the ceiling.
After lunch the weather improved a little so I decided on exploring the Devils Kitchen and Llyn Idwal area because of a dramatic painting of it in the hotel in similar weather.

I certainly is an impressive scene - more savage in its scale and rock scenery than anywhere I know in the lakes. The wildness of the experience was spoilt somewhat by the manufactured rock path and stairway which I had to follow. Even the ascent of the devils kitchen had been turned into a man-made affair. The whole footpath preservation stuff has really dimished the walk in my eyes. Having said that the surrounding are still savage and wild.

I was briefly tempted with a quick ascent of Glyder Fach but decided against it when three guys came down having had to turn around due to the high winds up there. So I just reached the Llyn above the Devils Kitchen and turned back.

Alt_Area: This was the re-introduction to Snowdonia that I had been planning for some time. I chose to climb  Carnedd Llewelyn from the wild Cwn Eigiau.

Hillnumber: First question was answered about Snowdonia - is this an area where you can escape the crowds easily and have the mountains to yourself. No -even on a work day with less than perfect weather at a remote start point I found myself the 4th car. I was booking up with the 5th car
Arearef: and the first 20 minutes of the walk was being stalked by this couple who seemed intent on staying behind me. I turned off through the ugly surrounding walls of Cwm Eigiau to look at the lake to let them pass. After this
Alt_Area: I didn't see many though until the area close to Carnedd Llewelyn.

Hillnumber: Enjoyed the area around Craig Ffynnon which felt quite lakeland-ish with lots of heather and little tarns. Lunch on "the witch" looking E over the lake. The area between this and Carnedd Llewelyn was the highlight - a sharp ridge followed by some scrambling to attain the summit ridge.
On the final ascent
Arearef: I was well aware that this is the highest mountain I have climbed since 2001
Alt_Area: plodding seemlingly endlessly upwards. It was cold on top with a biting wind. All the gear went on including the arctic buff and then I was at ease again
AreaLinkID: exploring the summit plateau. Views were extensive though quite dark due to alot of cloud just above the summits. Only Snowdon was in mist.

Hillnumber: Feeling quite tired on the descent
Arearef: toyed with missing out Foel Grach
Alt_Area: but bagged it quickly getting a second wind. The rest of the walk was done at a reasonable pace as I was driving over to Beddgelert that evening.
